Tools used
Hyper‑V – Virtualization platform used to build the entire network
Windows 10 VM – Workstation for IP configuration and connectivity testing
Kali Linux VM – Linux host for network commands and verification
pfSense Firewall – Open‑source firewall acting as the network backbone
Hyper‑V Virtual Switch Manager – Created the internal LAN environment
Windows CMD / PowerShell – Used for ipconfig and ping tests
Linux Terminal – Used for ip a and communication checks
Objective - To build a small, isolated virtual network using Windows, Kali Linux, and a pfSense firewall inside Hyper‑V. The goal was to configure static IPs, connect all systems through an internal switch, and verify host‑to‑host communication to demonstrate core networking and firewall fundamentals.
What I learned
How to create and manage multiple VMs in Hyper‑V
How internal virtual switches form isolated LANs
How to assign and verify static IP addresses
Differences between Windows and Linux networking
How to test communication using ping, ipconfig, and ip a
How a firewall sits inside a network and affects traffic flow
How devices communicate across the same subnet
Foundational skills for IT support, SOC, and blue‑team work
